A point $$P=[y_1, \dots, y_n, y_\infty, y_0, y_{n+3}]^\mathrm T$$ in the [[Lie quadric]] $$\mathscr L\subset\R\mathrm P^{n+2}$$ corresponds to a an oriented MÃ¶bius sphere in $$\widehat\R^n,$$ including points and hyperplanes. There are the following cases:

# <div>An oriented hypersphere with center $$c$$ and radius $$r\in\R$$:
$$\begin{bmatrix}
c \\ \|c\|^2-r^2 \\ 1 \\ r
\end{bmatrix}$$</div>

# <div>A point (point sphere) $$p\in\R^n$$:
$$\begin{bmatrix}
p \\ \|p\|^2 \\ 1 \\ 0
\end{bmatrix}$$</div>

# <div>An oriented hyperplane $$(n,u)=d$$ with normal $$n,$$ where $$(n,n)=1$$ and $$(\cdot,\cdot)$$ is the [[euclidean scalar product|Standardskalarprodukt in R]]:
$$\begin{bmatrix}
-n \\ -2d \\ 0 \\ 1
\end{bmatrix}$$</div>

# $$\infty\in\widehat\R^n$$ if $$P=[e_\infty].$$

Two points $$p_1,p_2$$ in the Lie quadric are [[polar|Pole-polar relationship]] to each other, i.e. $$\langle p_1,p_2\rangle=0,$$ if and only if the corresponding oriented spheres are in oriented contact.